### Pattern 6: Seeking by Timestamp

```java
public class TimestampConsumer {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Properties props = new Properties();
        props.put("bootstrap.servers", "localhost:9092");
        props.put("group.id", "timestamp-group");
        props.put("key.deserializer", StringDeserializer.class);
        props.put("value.deserializer", StringDeserializer.class);

        KafkaConsumer<String, String> consumer = new KafkaConsumer<>(props);
        consumer.subscribe(Arrays.asList("topic"));

        // Ensure metadata loaded
        consumer.poll(Duration.ofMillis(100));

        // Seek to 1 hour ago
        long oneHourAgo = System.currentTimeMillis() - 3600000;
        Map<TopicPartition, Long> timestampMap = new HashMap<>();

        for (TopicPartition partition : consumer.assignment()) {
            timestampMap.put(partition, oneHourAgo);
        }

        Map<TopicPartition, OffsetAndTimestamp> offsets = consumer.offsetsForTimes(timestampMap);

        for (Map.Entry<TopicPartition, OffsetAndTimestamp> entry : offsets.entrySet()) {
            if (entry.getValue() != null) {
                consumer.seek(entry.getKey(), entry.getValue().offset());
                System.out.println("Seeking " + entry.getKey() +
                    " to offset " + entry.getValue().offset());
            } else {
                // No data before timestamp, seek to end
                consumer.seekToEnd(Arrays.asList(entry.getKey()));
                System.out.println("No data 1 hour ago for " + entry.getKey() +
                    ", seeking to end");
            }
        }

        // Now consume from the timestamp
        try {
            while (true) {
                ConsumerRecords<String, String> records = consumer.poll(Duration.ofMillis(100));
                for (ConsumerRecord<String, String> record : records) {
                    System.out.println(record.value());
                }
            }
        } finally {
            consumer.close();
        }
    }
}
```

### Pattern 7: Error Recovery and Retry Logic

```java
public class ResilientConsumer {
    private static final int MAX_RETRIES = 3;
    private static final long RETRY_BACKOFF_MS = 1000;

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Properties props = new Properties();
        props.put("bootstrap.servers", "localhost:9092");
        props.put("group.id", "resilient-group");
        props.put("enable.auto.commit", false);
        props.put("key.deserializer", StringDeserializer.class);
        props.put("value.deserializer", StringDeserializer.class);

        boolean success = false;
        int retries = 0;

        while (!success && retries < MAX_RETRIES) {
            try {
                KafkaConsumer<String, String> consumer = new KafkaConsumer<>(props);
                consumer.subscribe(Arrays.asList("topic"));

                while (true) {
                    ConsumerRecords<String, String> records = consumer.poll(Duration.ofMillis(100));

                    for (ConsumerRecord<String, String> record : records) {
                        processWithRetry(record);
                    }

                    consumer.commitAsync((offsets, exception) -> {
                        if (exception != null) {
                            if (exception instanceof CommitFailedException) {
                                System.err.println("Fenced from group");
                                // Cannot recover - consumer must exit
                            } else {
                                System.err.println("Commit failed (will retry): " + exception);
                            }
                        }
                    });
                }
            } catch (CommitFailedException e) {
                System.err.println("Consumer fenced, creating new consumer");
                retries++;
                if (retries < MAX_RETRIES) {
                    try {
                        Thread.sleep(RETRY_BACKOFF_MS * retries);
                    } catch (InterruptedException ie) {
                        Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
                        break;
                    }
                }
            } catch (Exception e) {
                System.err.println("Unexpected error: " + e);
                retries++;
                if (retries < MAX_RETRIES) {
                    try {
                        Thread.sleep(RETRY_BACKOFF_MS * retries);
                    } catch (InterruptedException ie) {
                        Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
                        break;
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }

    private static void processWithRetry(ConsumerRecord<String, String> record)
            throws Exception {
        int retries = 0;
        Exception lastException = null;

        while (retries < MAX_RETRIES) {
            try {
                processRecord(record);
                return;  // Success
            } catch (Exception e) {
                lastException = e;
                retries++;
                if (retries < MAX_RETRIES) {
                    System.err.println("Processing failed, retrying: " + e.getMessage());
                    Thread.sleep(RETRY_BACKOFF_MS);
                }
            }
        }

        throw new Exception("Failed after " + MAX_RETRIES + " retries", lastException);
    }

    private static void processRecord(ConsumerRecord<String, String> record)
            throws Exception {
        System.out.println("Processing: " + record.value());
        // May throw exception if processing fails
    }
}
```

---

## Best Practices Summary

### 1. **Choose Commit Strategy Carefully**

- **Auto-commit**: Simple but loses progress on crash
- **Manual sync commit**: Safe but slower (blocks)
- **Manual async commit + sync on close**: Balanced (recommended)

### 2. **Always Use Rebalance Listener**

```java
consumer.subscribe(topics, new ConsumerRebalanceListener() {
    @Override
    public void onPartitionsRevoked(Collection<TopicPartition> partitions) {
        consumer.commitSync();  // Don't lose work
    }

    @Override
    public void onPartitionsAssigned(Collection<TopicPartition> partitions) {
        // Seek to committed position or custom position
    }
});
```

### 3. **Handle CommitFailedException Properly**

- Indicates consumer fenced by another member
- Must stop processing and create new consumer
- Don't retry or recover from same instance

### 4. **Set max.poll.interval.ms Appropriately**

- Must be larger than time to process one batch
- Larger values tolerate slower processing but slower rebalance
- Default 5 minutes usually sufficient

### 5. **Use Explicit Pause/Resume for Backpressure**

- Instead of discarding records, pause partitions
- Allows worker threads to catch up
- Maintains offset position

### 6. **Graceful Shutdown Pattern**

```java
try {
    while (running) {
        ConsumerRecords<String, String> records = consumer.poll(...);
        // Process...
    }
} catch (WakeupException e) {
    // Shutdown signal
} finally {
    consumer.commitSync();
    consumer.close();
}
```

### 7. **Test with Rebalancing**

- Kill/start consumers in group
- Verify offset commits work
- Ensure no message loss or duplication
- Test timeout scenarios

### 8. **Monitor Consumer Lag**

```java
Map<TopicPartition, Long> endOffsets = consumer.endOffsets(consumer.assignment());
long totalLag = 0;
for (TopicPartition tp : consumer.assignment()) {
    long position = consumer.position(tp);
    long lag = endOffsets.get(tp) - position;
    totalLag += lag;
}
System.out.println("Total lag: " + totalLag);
```

### 9. **Document Offset Reset Behavior**

- Make explicit decision about auto.offset.reset
- Document what happens on first run (earliest vs latest)
- Test offset reset scenarios

### 10. **Thread Safety Discipline**

- Never call consumer methods from different thread
- Use `wakeup()` only for shutdown signaling
- Synchronize shutdown flag with volatile or AtomicBoolean

---

## Gotchas and Common Mistakes

### Gotcha 1: Poll Blocks Longer Than Timeout During Rebalance

```java
// Timeout is 100ms, but poll blocks for 5 seconds!
consumer.poll(Duration.ofMillis(100));  // Rebalance happens here
// May block for seconds if rebalance callbacks are slow
```

**Fix:** Be aware rebalances don't respect timeout. Keep callback code fast.

### Gotcha 2: Committed Offset is "Next to Read", Not "Last Read"

```java
ConsumerRecord<String, String> record = records.get(0);
// record.offset() = 42

// To resume from this message:
consumer.seek(partition, 42);  // Wrong! Reads 42 again
consumer.seek(partition, 43);  // Correct! Next offset after 42

// Or in commit:
commitSync(Map.of(partition, new OffsetAndMetadata(43)));  // Not 42!
```

### Gotcha 3: Position Cleared on Rebalance Assignment

```java
consumer.seek(partition, 1000);

// Rebalance happens
// Position is cleared!

// In onPartitionsAssigned:
consumer.seek(partition, 1000);  // Must seek again
```

### Gotcha 4: Callbacks Execute During Poll

```java
long start = System.currentTimeMillis();
consumer.poll(Duration.ofMillis(100));
long elapsed = System.currentTimeMillis() - start;
System.out.println("Actual: " + elapsed + "ms");  // May be seconds!
// Rebalance callbacks run synchronously during poll()
```

### Gotcha 5: Can't Use Same Consumer Instance After Fencing

```java
try {
    consumer.commitSync();
} catch (CommitFailedException e) {
    // Don't continue using this consumer!
    consumer = new KafkaConsumer<>(props);  // Create new instance
}
```

### Gotcha 6: Unsubscribe Requires Poll to Complete

```java
consumer.unsubscribe();  // Just marks for removal
consumer.poll(Duration.ofMillis(100));  // Rebalance happens here
// Now actually unsubscribed
```

### Gotcha 7: Max Poll Interval Includes Processing Time

```java
while (true) {
    ConsumerRecords<String, String> records = consumer.poll(Duration.ofSeconds(10));

    for (ConsumerRecord<String, String> record : records) {
        // If this takes > max.poll.interval.ms total, FENCED!
        processSlowly(record);  // Takes 2 minutes per batch
    }
    // Never polls again within max.poll.interval.ms -> FENCED
}
```

### Gotcha 8: Pattern Subscription Discovers Topics on Metadata Refresh

```java
consumer.subscribe(Pattern.compile("logs-.*"));

// New topic "logs-2024" created
consumer.poll(...);  // May not discover immediately
// Wait for metadata.max.age.ms interval

// To discover faster:
consumer.poll(...);
Thread.sleep(1000);
consumer.poll(...);  // Now discovers new topic
```

---

## Summary Table: Key Concepts

| Concept | Definition | Key Property |
|---------|-----------|--------------|
| Position | Next offset to fetch | Increments on poll(), cleared on rebalance |
| Committed Offset | Last offset committed to broker | Recovered on rebalance, persists across restarts |
| Beginning Offset | Earliest available offset | After retention/compaction |
| End Offset | Highest offset + 1 | HIgh water mark |
| Poll | Fetch records, run callbacks, send heartbeats | Only place rebalances happen |
| Rebalance | Redistribute partitions across members | Triggered by subscribe changes, metadata refresh |
| Fencing | Consumer removed from group | Caused by session timeout or max poll timeout |
| Wakeup | Interrupt blocking poll | Only thread-safe method |

